ANOVA solves that problem by asking one global question first:

$$H_{0}: \mu_1 = \mu_2 = \mu_3 = \dots = \mu_k$$
$$H_{a}: \text{not all group means are equal}$$

If the global null hypothesis is rejected, we then ask which groups differ. That second step belongs to a post hoc procedure such as Tukey's HSD.

